==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: item
<hw>i"tem</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>See</ets>
<er>Iterate</er>.]</ety> <def>Also; as an additional article.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>item</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: item
<hw>i"tem</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Item</er>,
<pos>adv.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>An article; a separate particular in an account;
<as>as, the <ex>items</ex> in a bill; he picked up four <ex>items</ex>
at the drug store</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A hint; an innuendo.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A secret <qex>item</qex> was given to some of the bishops . . . to
absent themselves.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A short article in a newspaper; a paragraph; <as>as,
an <ex>item</ex> concerning the weather</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A topic or piece of information having the salacious
character of gossip, especially a romantic relation between two people;
<as>as, I hear that the boss and his new secretary are an
<ex>item</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Item</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Item
<hw>I"tem</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Itemed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Iteming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To make a note or memorandum
of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have <qex>itemed</qex> it in my memory.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>item-by-item</ent>⟦br⟧
